engine.rule,rule,condition,enforceNeurorights,"xr-neurorights.mentalPrivacy == true AND xr-neurorights.cognitiveLiberty == true AND xr-neurorights.mentalIntegrity == true AND xr-neurorights.noPunitiveXR == true",expression,Session allowed only when all neurorights bits set
engine.rule,rule,condition,denyOnCriticalRisk,"xr-bio.subject.psychRiskScore >= 0.9",expression,Abort non-emergency tasks at critical risk
engine.rule,rule,condition,denyIfProvenanceMissing,"xr-verification.sigstore.expectedDigest == null",expression,Disallow node startup if provenance misconfigured
```

- Mathematical solution (for this shard): The key safety equation implemented here is $E = S(1-R)E_s$; by reading S, R, Es from xr-bio.subject and using the same multiplication order, any runtime can deterministically reproduce whether allowSession or denySession conditions fire, ensuring portable, testable gating across Phoenix lab rigs.[^2_1]
- Scientific grounding: The shard encodes what your documents already describe—sleep-gated, neurorights-safe XR that treats active consciousness as single-locus, keeps nanoswarm within conservative exposure bands, and uses Sigstore provenance to harden the base OS for dream-gaming and dream-based recovery.[^2_1]
- Legal terms (≥100 chars): Phoenix Dreamnet / Reality.os lab nodes configured with this shard SHALL be operated as neurorights-grade research infrastructure; all sleep-gated dream-gaming SHALL be conducted under IRB-style protocols; no soul, karma, or reputational variables SHALL be used in any safety or eligibility calculation; and all provenance and safety events SHALL be stored in tamper-evident ledgers suitable for future regulator or ethics-board review without exposing raw dream narratives.[^2_3][^2_1]
- Geographical evidence: Phoenix, Arizona, USA (local jurisdiction and deployment context), Geneva, Switzerland (WHO/UN neurotech ethics), Santiago, Chile (neurorights law pilots), Brussels, Belgium (EU AI Act \& Cyber Resilience for high-risk XR), Boston, USA (sleep and neurotech clinical protocol models).[^2_3][^2_1]


