## Eligibility view shard ($E = S(1-R)E_s$ reproducibility)

**QPU.Datashard (.aln)**

```aln
aln
aln file xr-eligibility.closed-form.v1.aln
QPU.Datashard Eligibility view E = S(1-R)Es with cross-engine reproducibility

path,entitytype,field,key,value,datatype,constraints,notes
elig.view,view,scalar,theta,0.5,float,range0,1,Minimum eligibility threshold
elig.view,view,scalar,sleepToken,,float,range0,1,Imported S from sleep.subject
elig.view,view,scalar,psychRiskScore,,float,range0,1,Imported R from sleep.subject
elig.view,view,scalar,enStasisScore,,float,range0,1,Imported Es from sleep.subject

elig.view,view,formula,E,"clamp(sleepToken,0,1) * (1 - clamp(psychRiskScore,0,1)) * clamp(enStasisScore,0,1)",string,readonly,E = S(1-R)Es
elig.view,view,condition,allowHighImpact,"E >= theta",expression,Allow high-fidelity dream-gaming
elig.view,view,condition,softenOrDeny,"E < theta",expression,Soften haptics or deny XR-deep
```

- Mathematical solution: To reproduce $E$, each engine clamps S, R, Es into $[0,1]$, computes $1-R$, multiplies S, $(1-R)$, and Es, then clamps E into $[0,1]$; using the same clamp and multiplication order guarantees identical E from identical inputs in Rust, C++, or ALN interpreters.[^3_1]
- Scientific grounding: Your Rust SafetyVector already implements compute_eligibility_e with the same clamped formula, so this shard is a direct algebraic projection of a working implementation, not a theoretical construct.[^3_1]
- Legal terms: The eligibility function $E = S(1-R)E_s$ SHALL serve only as a safety and comfort gate for dream-gaming intensity, SHALL never embed or infer moral value, karma, or reputation, and SHALL be published with test vectors so regulators in Santiago, Geneva, and Brussels can independently confirm cross-platform reproducibility.[^3_2]
- Geographical evidence: Santiago, Chile (neurorights framing of mental integrity), Geneva, Switzerland (OHCHR documents on mental privacy), Brussels, Belgium (AI Act technical documentation requirements), Seattle, USA (Rust ecosystem for XR engines), Phoenix, Arizona, USA (lab rigs and edge nodes used for cross-engine testing).[^3_2][^3_1]

