# This research focuses on technical validation of the closed-loop integration between biometric inputs and safety-critical computational modules in the Phoenix Dreamnet / Reality.os system. The primary aim is to confirm that multiple engines (lab rigs, edge nodes) produce identical outputs for the eligibility metric E = S(1−R)Es, nanoswarm doseRatio, and compliance scores when processing the same QPU.Datashard inputs. The scope includes empirical tuning of sleep-gated eligibility thresholds, psychrisk-aware haptic/scene intensity envelopes, and Cyberswarm tissue-dose constraints, all grounded in polysomnography and radiobiology. These modular safety layers—sleep-gate rules, eligibility views, neurorights policies, Sigstore provenance, and state-only AI tunnels—are treated as testable, mathematically defined components that must compose into a unified system delivering addiction-breaking behavioral shifts and carbon reduction without accessing or exporting raw dream content. Policy analysis of alignment with Chilean neurorights law, EU AI Act, and UN neuroethics principles runs in parallel but is secondary to platform-agnostic technical reproducibility. Geographic contexts include Phoenix (deployment), Boston (sleep science), Geneva (neuroethics), Santiago (neurorights law), and Brussels (AI regulation). The research explicitly excludes soul-related constructs, karma systems, reputational scoring, and any handling of raw neural or dream narrative data.

