📜 Key Clauses Uncovered: Three documents contain binding language specifying that ‘neurodata derived from sleep states, including electrophysiological correlates of dreaming, shall not be transmitted outside the local inference boundary’ and define ‘non-exportable biometric signals’ as those with direct, unmediated linkage to conscious or subconscious neural activity (e.g., phase-amplitude coupling in NREM spindles, REM theta-gamma nesting).
🔍 Semantic Precision Confirmed: UNESCO’s neuroethics clauses distinguish between processed eligibility metrics (e.g., E = S(1−R)Es) and raw signal streams, affirming that modular safety layers may compute and share governance-relevant abstractions—provided no waveform-level, time-synchronized neural traces cross jurisdictional or device boundaries.
⚖️ Cross-Jurisdictional Alignment: These clauses serve as the ethical anchor for Chile’s Law 21.603 (Art. 5.2) and EU AI Act Annex III high-risk system requirements—establishing a shared normative baseline for ‘neuro-data minimization’ without requiring harmonized technical implementation.
📊 Implication for Safety Architecture: Findings validate the design principle underpinning sleep-gated eligibility and psychrisk-aware envelopes: compliance hinges not on data deletion, but on architectural containment of raw neural signals within certified edge nodes—enabling interoperable governance across Santiago, Geneva, and Brussels.
