# Benchmarking QPU.Datashard Reproducibility for E = S(1−R)Es Across Lab Rig and Edge Node Deployments

🔬 Core Investigation: Launched six high-precision, time-bound searches (all constrained to before:2026-01-06, with three also requiring after:2024-06-01 or after:2023-01-01) to rigorously test computational equivalence between Phoenix Dreamnet and Reality.os — specifically whether identical QPU.Datashard inputs yield bit-for-bit or numerically identical outputs for the sleep-gated eligibility function E = S(1−R)Es, nanoswarm doseRatio, and final compliance score.
⚙️ Technical Scope: Queries explicitly target executable logic (not just documentation), numerical calibration parameters, and empirical dose–response validation — including REM density → haptic cap % mappings, HRV LF/HF weighting coefficients, and polysomnography-to-behavioral-outcome causal links (e.g., startle potentiation, cortisol-AUC, EEG theta/beta shift).
🌐 Source Targeting: Prioritized authoritative technical domains: phoenixdreamnet.org, realityos.dev, github.com/reality-os, arxiv.org, nature.com, and icrp.org — while excluding policy frameworks (e.g., EU AI Act, Santiago neurorights law) due to lack of implementation-level detail.
📉 Early Signal Detection: One search returned 6 relevant pages — focused on UNESCO’s 2021 neuroethics recommendation defining non-exportable raw polysomnographic signals, reinforcing the regulatory sensitivity around QPU.Datashard’s biometric provenance. Five other queries yielded zero results — indicating critical gaps in publicly available, time-stamped, cross-platform reproducibility reports for lab rig vs. edge node deployments.
📊 Validation Thresholds: All active investigations require deterministic, hardware-agnostic thresholds — e.g., <±0.001 numerical tolerance for E computation across platforms, standardized PSG input sampling (256 Hz, ±2 µV resolution), and explicit Cyberswarm tissue-dose limits traceable to ICRP microdosimetry RBE models.
