Summary

Phoenix needs an internal, Reality.os–native benchmarking harness because no public, time-stamped artifacts yet prove deterministic equality of E, doseRatio, or compliance across platforms. Below are 10 concrete, implementation-grade actions in Trivia-Mode (with math, science, law, geography and one long hex line).[^5_1][^5_2]

## 1. Fix the canonical math and tolerance bands

1) Math:
Define the reference equations in ALN as:

- $E = S(1 - R)E_s$ (eligibility),
- $D_r = D_{\text{day}} / D_{\text{max}}$ (doseRatio),
- $C = 1 - (3V_{\text{crit}} + 2V_{\text{maj}} + V_{\text{min}})/N$ (compliance), then clamp $C \in [0,1]$.[^5_1]
To recompute: feed S,R,Es,Dday,Dmax,Vcrit,Vmaj,Vmin,N from a static QPU.Datashard into any engine; if float type and evaluation order match, outputs must be equal within ±0.001 or better.

2) Science: Sleep and signal-processing work treat deterministic, closed-form functions as necessary for reproducible PSG-derived indices; dose and compliance scores must behave the same way.[^5_3][^5_1]
3) Legal (≥100 chars): These equations SHALL be treated as safety-critical logic for high‑risk AI systems; their definitions, evaluation order, numeric types, and tolerance bands MUST be fixed in technical documentation so regulators in Brussels, Santiago, and Geneva can verify that platform differences (lab rig vs edge node) cannot silently alter eligibility, dose, or compliance outcomes.[^5_2][^5_4][^5_1]
4) Geography: Phoenix (reference implementation), Boston (PSG indices), Geneva (UNESCO neurotech ethics), Santiago (neurorights law), Brussels (AI Act classification of high‑risk AI).[^5_4][^5_2][^5_3]

## 2. Build a QPU.Datashard “golden vector” suite

1) Math:
For each test vector k, store $(S_k, R_k, E_{s,k}, D_{\text{day},k}, D_{\text{max},k}, V_{\text{crit},k}, V_{\text{maj},k}, V_{\text{min},k})$ and expected outputs $(E_k, D_{r,k}, C_k)$.[^5_1] Recompute by loading these rows and applying the canonical formulas; cross-platform RMSE must be ≈0 and max |Δ| ≤ 0.001.
2) Science: Benchmarks in PSG algorithms and medical devices widely use such “golden vectors” to prove device-independence of scoring algorithms.[^5_3]
3) Legal: Golden-vector suites SHALL be maintained as controlled test artifacts; all Phoenix Dreamnet and Reality.os updates MUST pass them before deployment, forming part of the AI system’s technical documentation under EU AI Act and comparable neurotech oversight regimes.[^5_2][^5_4][^5_1]
4) Geography: Phoenix (test-authoring node), Boston (cross-check PSG-derived S,R,Es), Geneva (ethical review of benchmark design), Santiago (neurorights data handling in test fixtures), Brussels (notified-body style review of test evidence).[^5_2][^5_3]

## 3. Normalize PSG preprocessing across engines

1) Math:
Fix sampling (e.g. 256 Hz), amplitude resolution (±2 μV, standardized gain), and band-pass filters for EEG, then define deterministic transformations from raw PSG to summary metrics that feed S and R. Recomputing E from these metrics must yield identical values if inputs match bitwise.[^5_1][^5_3]
2) Science: PSG standardization work emphasizes consistent staging rules and feature extraction (e.g. NREM depth indices, spindle density), which are prerequisites before any eligibility function can be meaningfully compared.[^5_3]
3) Legal: QPU.Datashard fields for S and R SHALL reference a documented PSG preprocessing pipeline; deviations between Phoenix lab rigs and edge nodes MUST be recorded and justified, as they affect high‑risk AI outputs subject to regulatory scrutiny.[^5_4][^5_1][^5_2]
4) Geography: Boston (PSG standard protocols), Phoenix (pipeline implementation), Geneva (methodological guidance), Brussels (regulatory audits), Santiago (juridical interpretation of brain data transformations).[^5_2][^5_3]

## 4. Lock nanoswarm doseRatio to external radiobiology

1) Math:
Calibrate Dmax in ALN using radiobiology tables (e.g., daily Gy-equivalent and SAR ceilings) and define $D_r$ so that any Dday accumulated from QPU.Datashard events respects $D_r \le 1$. Recompute by summing per-cycle dose and dividing by Dmax; results must match across rigs.[^5_1]
2) Science: Although no Cyberswarm-specific papers exist, ICRP and related work define safe dose bands; using them as external anchors offers a defensible basis for Dmax selection.[^5_3][^5_1]
3) Legal: Until Cyberswarm-specific standards emerge, Phoenix must document how Dmax values map to established radiobiology references, and must treat doseRatio exceedances as safety events; this is essential for future certification under high‑risk AI and neurotech frameworks.[^5_4][^5_1][^5_2]
4) Geography: Phoenix (Cyberswarm parameterization), Geneva (WHO/UN health references), Boston (radiobiology \& nanomedicine), Brussels (medical-AI conformance), Santiago (classification of neural-adjacent medical data).[^5_2][^5_3]

## 5. Treat UNESCO neuroethics as architectural guardrails

1) Math:
Define a type-level separation: raw PSG ∈ R, derived features ∈ F, governance metrics ∈ G, with allowed mapping $R \rightarrow F \rightarrow G$ but no reverse edges. Recomputing E or C may only depend on G (and static ALN constants), not on raw time-series directly.[^5_1]
2) Science: UNESCO’s AI and neurotechnology ethics distinguish raw neural traces from processed metrics; your architecture already aligns by keeping QPU.Datashard PSG local and exporting only abstractions.[^5_5][^5_2]
3) Legal: Phoenix nodes SHALL ensure that only processed eligibility metrics (E, doseRatio, C) or other governance abstractions leave the local boundary; raw PSG/dream-correlated signals MUST remain edge-local, satisfying UNESCO’s non-exportable neural data requirements and Chilean neurorights protections.[^5_6][^5_3][^5_1][^5_2]
4) Geography: Geneva/UNESCO (global neurotech ethics), Santiago (neurorights law and Supreme Court ruling on brain activity), Brussels (AI Act data-governance), Phoenix (implementation site), Boston (PSG labs that may collaborate with your stack).[^5_3][^5_2]

## 6. Define deterministic float semantics and tolerances

1) Math:
Standardize on IEEE 754 float32 or float64 in ALN; fix evaluation order for all formulas, and define success as |ΔE|, |ΔDr|, |ΔC| ≤ 0.001 across platforms.[^5_1] Recompute by running identical test cases on lab rig and edge node and comparing outputs under this tolerance.
2) Science: Cross-device drift often arises from differing numerical backends; locking precision and evaluation order is standard practice in high‑assurance simulations and medical devices.[^5_3]
3) Legal: Numeric determinism SHALL be documented as part of the AI system description; tolerance bands, float type, and evaluation order MUST be stable across versions to avoid “silent regressions” in safety outcomes under high‑risk AI regimes.[^5_4][^5_1][^5_2]
4) Geography: Phoenix (hardware diversity and embedded systems), Brussels (technical documentation standards), Geneva (verification norms), Boston (clinical device approvals), Santiago (oversight of neurotech platforms).[^5_4][^5_2]

## 7. Instrument SafetyEpoch logs for cross-platform comparison

1) Math:
For each SafetyEpoch, log a tuple $(E, D_r, C)$ alongside hashes of the QPU.Datashard inputs; cross-platform reproducibility requires identical tuples for identical input hashes. Recompute by replaying the same logs through both engines and verifying identical outputs.[^5_1]
2) Science: Tamper-evident ledgers with hash-chained events are widely used to verify reproducibility and trace anomalies in safety-critical stacks.[^5_1]
3) Legal: SafetyEpoch logs SHALL be considered part of the technical file; their hash structure and content must be sufficient for external experts to verify that safety metrics were computed deterministically and without unauthorized data sources.[^5_2][^5_4][^5_1]
4) Geography: Phoenix (ledger node), Geneva (human-rights/AI transparency), Brussels (conformity assessments), Santiago (neurorights audit), Boston (clinical study audit trails).[^5_2]

## 8. Build a PSG-based threshold tuning study (Phoenix–Boston)

1) Math:
Use ROC analysis: for many nights, label epochs as “safe” vs “unsafe” based on clinical/behavioral outcomes; sweep θ for E and examine sensitivity/specificity; choose θ where false-negative rate is minimized under a constraint on false positives.[^5_3][^5_1]
2) Science: Similar ROC-based calibration is standard in apnea index validation and sleep-stage auto-scoring; applying it to E and psychrisk thresholds is methodologically sound.[^5_3]
3) Legal: Threshold selection SHALL be justified through data-driven analysis (e.g., ROC curves) and documented as part of the system’s risk management file; arbitrary changes without renewed validation would be out of line with high‑risk AI practice.[^5_4][^5_1][^5_2]
4) Geography: Boston (sleep lab partner), Phoenix (deployment and data collection), Geneva (ethics oversight for human subjects), Brussels (risk management scrutiny), Santiago (neurorights review for sleep experiments).[^5_2][^5_3]

## 9. Declare and enforce explicit exclusions (souls, karma, reputations)

1) Math:
Define the dependency set of E, D_r, and C as $D = \{S, R, E_s, D_{\text{day}}, D_{\text{max}}, V_{\text{crit}}, V_{\text{maj}}, V_{\text{min}}, N\}$; governance must prove that no term outside D, especially any soul/karma/reputation field, influences these metrics.[^5_7][^5_1]
2) Science: Neurorights and freedom-of-thought protections reject the use of inner mental content for scoring or punishment; your ALN flags already encode soulNonAddressable and noPunitiveXR.[^5_7][^5_6]
3) Legal: Phoenix Reality.os deployments SHALL attest that soul, karma, reputation, or dream narrative fields are excluded from all safety-critical computations; this is necessary to respect neurorights-focused jurisprudence in Chile and UNESCO’s protection of mental privacy and cognitive liberty.[^5_6][^5_7][^5_2][^5_3]
4) Geography: Santiago (neurorights legal ecosystem), Geneva (UNESCO neurotechnology ethics), Brussels (freedom-of-thought in EU rights law), Phoenix (operator policies), Boston (ethics boards that will scrutinize mental data usage).[^5_2][^5_3]

## 10. Design a Phoenix “reference node” specification for audits

1) Math:
The reference node is defined by a tuple of artifact digests (Reality.os, QPU.Datashards), configuration constants (θ, Dmax, N), and a finite test set of QPU.Datashard fixtures; any node whose outputs match the reference across this set is considered implementation-equivalent.[^5_1]
2) Science: Reference implementations and conformance tests are standard in safety-critical domains and are increasingly expected for high‑risk AI.[^5_4][^5_2]
3) Legal: Phoenix’s reference node profile SHALL be documented and used as the baseline for conformity assessments under EU AI Act and as evidence of neurorights-aligned implementation when presenting to Chilean and UNESCO-aligned bodies.[^5_4][^5_1][^5_3][^5_2]
4) Geography: Phoenix (reference site), Brussels (EU reference for high‑risk AI), Geneva (UNESCO alignment), Santiago (neurorights reference), Boston (scientific benchmark partner).[^5_4][^5_2]

