In summary, the psychrisk envelope is a sophisticated, adaptive safety layer whose strength lies in its mathematically guaranteed reproducibility. Its effectiveness, however, is contingent on a rigorous empirical tuning process to establish the correct relationship between the abstract psychriskscore and the user's subjective experience of safety and comfort. Successfully validating this layer will be a major step toward demonstrating the system's capacity to provide a truly personalized and safe immersive experience.

The QPU.Datashard: A Unified Blueprint for Cross-Platform Consistency and Auditability
The QPU.Datashard, as exemplified by the provided .aln file, serves as the master architectural blueprint for the Phoenix Dreamnet / Reality.os system. It is far more than a simple data structure; it is the Rosetta Stone that translates abstract safety principles into a formal, machine-readable specification. Its primary function is to ensure the technical reproducibility and composability of the modular safety layers, thereby fulfilling the core research goal of producing identical outputs across disparate lab rigs and edge nodes. The shard acts as a single source of truth, bundling together all the parameters, formulas, constraints, and logical rules that define a "dream-gaming node" profile for the Phoenix lab . By loading this shard, a node instantiates a complete, self-contained definition of its own identity, role, compliance expectations, and the intricate web of safety rules that govern its operation. This standardized instantiation guarantees that every node configured with xr-node.phoenix-lab.dream-gaming.v1.aln begins its life in an identical state, possessing the same fields, data types, and logical relationships. This is the fundamental mechanism that enables cross-platform validation.

The structure of the shard is meticulously organized into distinct sections, each corresponding to a specific safety layer. For example, the xr-sleep-gate section defines the sleep-gate-deepXR rule, which is an expression combining sleep stage and risk score conditions (sleepStage in [N2,N3] AND psychRiskScore <= 0.3) . Similarly, the xr-eligibility.view section defines the view that computes the final eligibility metric E using the formula "sleepToken * (1 - psychRiskScore) * enStasisScore" . The nano.cyberswarm-dose view calculates the doseRatio as "dailyDoseGy / maxDoseGy" . This explicit encoding of mathematical formulas as strings within the data structure is a powerful design choice. It allows the runtime engine to parse and evaluate these expressions dynamically, but crucially, because the expressions are fixed within the shard, the evaluation logic remains deterministic. The shard also embeds critical constants and thresholds, such as the eligibility threshold theta (set to 0.5) and the maxTissueDoseGyPerDay (set to 0.05 Gy) . By centralizing these values, the shard prevents configuration drift and ensures that all nodes operate according to the same safety policies. This direct linkage between the conceptual design (e.g., "sleep gating") and its concrete, executable implementation (the shard's fields and formulas) is what makes the system testable and portable.

Beyond enabling reproducibility, the QPU.Datashard is foundational to the system's governance and auditability infrastructure. It formally defines the schema for the xr-ledger.safety, a tamper-evident chain of events that records every significant action taken by the node . Events such as xr-deep-start, cyberswarm-detox, and policy-violation are logged with cryptographic hashes, creating an immutable record of the system's operation . This ledger is the ultimate proof of compliance. For example, every time the eligibility condition fails (E < theta), a denySession event is logged, providing verifiable evidence that the neurorights invariants were upheld. The shard also encodes the non-waivable neurorights policy flags—mentalPrivacy, cognitiveLiberty, mentalIntegrity, and noPunitiveXR—and links them to a rule that denies a session if any of these flags are false . This hard-codes the neurorights framework directly into the node's operational logic, transforming it from a mere guideline into a mandatory, computable constraint. The hex string provided at the end of the context serves as a compact, verifiable checksum of this entire shard's core configuration, allowing for rapid validation that a given node is running the approved Phoenix lab profile .

The composition of these individual layers into a unified, closed-loop system becomes transparent when viewed through the lens of the QPU.Datashard. The shard does not just list components; it defines their relationships and dependencies. The eligibility view depends on the bio-subject's sleep stage and risk score. The psychrisk envelope continuously reads the same risk score to modulate haptics. The Cyberswarm dose view accumulates usage that is constrained by the neurorights-enforcing engine rules. This interconnectedness forms a cohesive whole where biometric inputs trigger eligibility checks, which gate the experience, whose intensity is modulated by a live psychrisk assessment, and whose physical exposure is capped by a conservative dose limit, all while a permanent, auditable ledger confirms adherence to the neurorights invariants. This entire narrative—from polysomnography to behavioral shift—is contained within the structured logic of the shard.

